00:06.697 --> 00:24.132
Another area of research that has been done here 
and reported in several places, including one of

00:06.697 --> 00:24.132
the held in Brazil, and two years ago, almost two 
years ago, at the first Latin American Polity

00:24.112 --> 00:43.995
Congress, which was held in Mexico City, this 
subject was reported. But it is a very popular area

00:44.696 --> 00:49.562
of concern among institutional as well as 
industry people at the present time, and that is

00:49.542 --> 01:03.466
the so-called recycling of poultry wastes. And we 
did some work on this, actually recycling it to In

01:13.218 --> 01:37.676
the poultry, the most common usage of the 
recycling of the nutrients and the actual feed

01:13.218 --> 01:37.676
wastage from the troughs and also the undigested 
material going through the birds, you see, plus

01:13.218 --> 01:37.676
what little they can get from the litter that they 
use for growing the birds. They call this... DPW,

01:40.758 --> 01:50.813
dried poultry waste, and it has been used rather 
extensively for feeding of cattle. It is still

01:52.075 --> 02:02.631
frowned upon, its use is still frowned upon by the 
FDA because they are afraid of a

02:03.674 --> 02:13.906
additives that may still be in the material and 
thus pick it up as residues in the tissues. But the

02:14.807 --> 02:29.344
people, the industry people, are very careful 
about this and they normally do not use it if

02:14.807 --> 02:29.344
there's any possibility of contamination of the 
tissues of animals. But in 1969, we published,

02:29.628 --> 02:44.430
that's five years ago, we published an article 
which covered two years of work with laying hens

02:29.628 --> 02:44.430
where we recycled this. litter from three 
different sources, from the broilers and from

02:44.613 --> 02:59.609
laying hens and from pullets that had been raised 
to laying age. And these three sources of the DPW,

02:59.629 --> 03:12.983
or dried poultry waste, and we used this and used it 
at 10 and 20 percent levels and got very good

02:59.629 --> 03:12.983
results. It can be reused. In other words, we only 
reused it one time, but it probably could be

03:14.825 --> 03:26.900
recycled again and again, particularly if it's 
used with cattle, I'm quite sure, that can be

03:14.825 --> 03:26.900
reused. And so we think we were fairly early in our 
interest in this area and actually did some

03:27.440 --> 03:35.730
experimental work in this area.

03:42.477 --> 03:50.631
I've noted that a large percentage of the work that 
you have done on chickens has been with laying

03:42.477 --> 03:50.631
hens. How did you come to settle upon laying hens as 
opposed to broilers or some other aspect? Well,

03:57.482 --> 04:06.654
that's a very good question, and it has perhaps a 
surprising answer, but not necessarily so. You

04:07.615 --> 04:18.188
will recall that when I entered the poultry 
department at Texas A&M University, I entered it

04:07.615 --> 04:18.188
as head of the department in an administrative 
position. And so we were affected in the same way

04:18.168 --> 04:28.017
that almost all institutions are. You never have 
enough financial support to do all of the things

04:28.478 --> 04:35.284
that you and your staff want to do. So you have to 
sort of set up priorities and use your funds in this

04:35.965 --> 04:42.291
fashion. Well, this being true, you see, that 
there is... rarely, if ever, enough funds to do all

04:47.716 --> 04:54.233
the things that a scientific staff wants to do. It 
was quite important, being head of the

04:55.356 --> 05:03.717
department, that I try to set up a research program 
were there would be no opportunity for staff to

05:03.697 --> 05:20.616
feel that the department head was using his 
authority to take funds ahead of somebody else who

05:03.697 --> 05:20.616
needed them, you see. And when I first started this 
program, At the laying hens, my research with

05:25.988 --> 05:41.549
laying hens has majorly been designed in the 
applied or practical kind of areas rather than in

05:25.988 --> 05:41.549
the highly basic or scientific areas. And this is 
also purposely set up because At the time the

05:46.475 --> 06:08.803
program started, the income from the sale of 
surplus eggs from the experiments was that the

05:46.475 --> 06:08.803
price of eggs was generally high enough to pay for 
the feed, the labor, and so that actually the

05:46.475 --> 06:08.803
research program of the laying hens was 
self-supporting. And therefore, I could use the

06:09.340 --> 06:27.320
sales returns from the research program and feel 
free of not being misunderstood in terms of

06:09.340 --> 06:27.320
priorities, administrative priorities, for the 
research program. And so that is the reason why

06:27.861 --> 06:33.087
this was picked. In the case of broilers, if the 
price of broilers was high at the time you marketed

06:33.067 --> 06:41.020
your birds, then you probably got some returns. 
But if, on the other hand, it was low, you might have

06:41.521 --> 06:45.888
lost some money. But at that time, laying hands, 
now it happens that actually the price of eggs in

06:46.228 --> 06:57.066
the meantime have changed so that currently you'd 
be subject to the same danger. that you would

06:57.046 --> 06:58.608
withdraw this. But in those days, it was not so, and 
this determined two things. That I would pick

07:04.113 --> 07:24.353
laying hens for my experimental program, and that 
I'd pick the productive, applied efficiency

07:04.113 --> 07:24.353
areas, management and so on, those areas of 
research, rather than the costly, basic type of

07:04.113 --> 07:24.353
research. That way you would leave the funds 
appropriated by the state for the other members of

07:24.788 --> 07:30.838
the department. Yes, yes. And I was very careful 
for them to see the budgets as the appropriations

07:31.580 --> 07:43.320
were made each year, and also for them to see what 
they had available for their programs. And I

07:43.300 --> 07:47.767
think, as far as I know, I did not have complaints. I 
might not have ever heard them, if there's been

07:47.887 --> 07:50.551
any. But I was real proud of the fact that I 
overheard little and no complaints because of

07:51.112 --> 07:58.903
this. And it was done purposely for this reason. 
You mentioned just a minute ago about for a long

08:02.437 --> 08:12.371
time eggs were kind of a steady cash crop, but now 
the price tends to fluctuate more than it did in the

08:02.437 --> 08:12.371
past. Yes, and not only that, but the margins, the 
egg production units have become so large. There

08:19.921 --> 08:26.250
used to be a fairly large margin between the cost of 
production and the sale price of the eggs. But now,

08:26.230 --> 08:39.229
because the units have gotten so big—now, I don't 
know which is cause and which is—well, I do, too,

08:26.230 --> 08:39.229
but it could be rationalized which is cause and 
which is effect. But the units are so large today

08:39.249 --> 08:51.107
that they have to be that way because the margins 
have gotten so narrow between the actual

08:39.249 --> 08:51.107
production cost price cost and the sale price of 
the eggs. And for that reason, there isn't much

08:58.323 --> 09:03.574
margin left there. And so you're very close to the 
same kind of a fluctuating pattern that we have in

09:03.975 --> 09:10.750
broilers.

