have been, but they were, and so for that reason, we 
believe that THIS ENTERED IN TO THE

13:48.830 --> 13:53.876
availability for some of the foreign 
assignments. By caged layers, you mean is each

13:55.017 --> 14:00.203
chicken in an individual cage? At first they 
majorly were housed this way, but very quickly

14:00.223 --> 14:12.236
they, and a lot of the work was done here that showed 
that it could be done otherwise. The cost of

14:13.297 --> 14:16.761
building a cage for one bird is fairly high. So what 
they did, they started putting what we call higher

14:19.605 --> 14:24.513
density. In other words, we put two birds per cage, 
three birds per cage. In a few cases, the cages

14:28.359 --> 14:33.287
would be a little bigger in size. But the density, 
the square footage of the cage area allowed per

14:33.307 --> 14:42.040
bird was reduced as we added more birds. And so the 
common practice now is to house from three to five

14:42.020 --> 14:49.752
birds per cage per unit. And you get more eggs at 
less cost in this method than by letting the birds

14:51.082 --> 14:57.109
run free? If they're properly managed. They have 
to be de-beaked, keep them picking each other.

15:02.014 --> 15:03.977
They have to be properly fed. And the diets have 
been increased in density because there is more

15:04.437 --> 15:10.384
competition between birds. There's both social 
competition between birds, and there's also

15:10.724 --> 15:18.473
mechanical competition for water and feeder 
space. And so if they're properly managed, and all

15:18.453 --> 15:36.416
of this had to be investigated experimentally in 
order to supply industry with some of the answers

15:18.453 --> 15:36.416
to some of the questions and solutions to some of 
the problems they had in doing this. And

15:37.657 --> 15:48.291
